commit.message: Mention the project's end of life status.

Add Dockerfile and build script for manylinux2014

As a parting gift, I built a manylinux2014 wheel for this project.
Python 2 has reached EOL as has this project.  If that wheel does not
work out for anyone, the only thing I can spend any time doing is simply
removing it from PyPI...
I dub thee 3.5.4.

GitHub [#57]: Fix unpickling of our exceptions.

https://github.com/google/python-subprocess32/issues/57

3.5.4rc2
Install twine on macOS for the CI build + upload.
Add the ChangeLog entry, dub this 3.5.4b1.

Handle "broken pipe" errors in communicate on short lived processes [GH-62]

This goes into the direction of this commit:
  https://github.com/python/cpython/commit/a5e881d2e8ad7e91ff801a02be9de924705d9a6e

Backports the fixes for https://bugs.python.org/issue10963, https://bugs.python.org/issue19612, and https://bugs.python.org/issue30418.

When a child process was so short lived it dies or closes its pipes before you call communicate(), when supplying input or reading its output do not raise an unexpected exception for the broken pipe or interrupted system call.

Spelling fix in Changelog (#58)

Minor fix :)
3.5.3 was released, mark this as 3.5.4b0.
Call this 3.5.3.

commit.message:
Functional test for restore_signals, include signal.h. (#51)

restore_signals=True lacked a functional test.

It was possible, though unlikely in my experience, to build the extension module against a Python interpreter that was not already including <signal.h> via Python.h.  I believe this might have happened on builds that did not enable --with-fpectl?  The Debian CPython 2.7.13 package does not exhibit the problem.

Regardless, testing for signal.h and explicitly including it is always the right thing to do.

commit.message: delcare 3.5.0

Run autoconf before building the extension. #40 (#48)

Add an autoconf script to test for features.
Run autoconf at setuptools build_ext time.

Python 2.x's configure script does not test for the more recent
features we use so their defines are not in pyconfig.h.  We run
our own autoconf to verify those and use its generated header
to pick those up.

Getting configure to run via setuptools is... wacky. :/

also, internal: Run python2 tests first, get rid of the old .hgtags file.
